               <head>Epistle collections: Augustine, Ambrose, Becket</head>
               <msContents>
                  <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="St_Johns_College_MS_15-item1">
                     <locus from="1v" to="114v">Fols. 1<hi rend="superscript">va</hi>–114<hi
                           rend="superscript">va</hi>:</locus>
                     <incipit>Dilectissimo et in cristi membris honorando fratri valentino et
                        fratribus <gap reason="editorial"/> Cresconium felicem et alium felicem dei
                        seruos qui ex vestra congregacione</incipit>
                     <explicit>facere soleas vel faciendum esse reperias</explicit>
                     <finalRubric>Expliciunt epistole AUGUSTINI doctoris</finalRubric>
                     <author key="person_66806872">AUGUSTINE</author>
                     <title key="work_801" type="desc">Epistle collection</title>
                     <note><bibl><title>CPL</title> 262</bibl>, <bibl>ed. Al. Goldbacher, <hi
                              rend="italic">CSEL</hi> 34 (1895–8), 44 (1904), 57 (1911), 58 (1923)
                           variously</bibl>. There are four <title key="work_17092" type="desc"
                           >indices</title>, two by the main scribe: (a) a list of the 142 epistles
                           <locus from="1r" to="1v">(1<hi rend="superscript">ra–va</hi>)</locus>;
                        (b) a table giving for each the ‘intencio epistolarum’ <locus from="114v"
                           to="116r">(fols. 114<hi rend="superscript">va</hi>–16<hi
                              rend="superscript">rb</hi>)</locus>; (c) an alphabetical index of
                        major topics <locus from="116r" to="119v">(fols. 116<hi rend="superscript"
                              >rb</hi>–19<hi rend="superscript">vb</hi>)</locus>; (d) a list of the
                        epistles identifying addressees (<locus from="120r" to="120r">fol. 120<hi
                              rend="superscript">rac</hi></locus>, three columns). About half of
                           <locus from="120r" to="120r">fol. 120<hi rend="superscript"
                           >rc</hi></locus> and the entire verso are blank.</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="2" xml:id="St_Johns_College_MS_15-item2">
                     <locus from="121r" to="171v">Fols. 121<hi rend="superscript">ra</hi>–71<hi
                           rend="superscript">va</hi>:</locus>
                     <incipit>AMBROSIUS iusto de significacione didragmi cuius dimidium hebreus
                        recipitur <gap reason="editorial"/> Pvlcre admones frater iuste vt
                        epistolares fabulas et sermonem absentium</incipit>
                     <explicit>conuertant meo sanguine sitim suam expleant</explicit>
                     <author key="person_100227669">AMBROSE</author>
                     <title key="work_482" type="desc">Epistle collection</title>
                     <note><bibl>CPL 160</bibl>, <bibl>ed. Otto Faller and Michaela Zelzer,
                              <title>CSEL</title> 82, 3 vols. (1968–82), 1–3:125</bibl>, ending with
                        10.76. An <title key="work_17092" type="desc">index</title>, which includes
                        the next three items as if they were part of this text, appears at <locus
                           from="182r" to="182v">fol. 182<hi rend="superscript">rb–vb</hi></locus>,
                        copied by the main scribe, although in a significantly larger hand than
                        elsewhere.</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="3" xml:id="St_Johns_College_MS_15-item3">
                     <locus from="171v" to="174v">Fols. 171<hi rend="superscript">va</hi>–74<hi
                           rend="superscript">vb</hi>:</locus>
                     <rubric>De obitu Theodosij imperatoris et de eius laude lxxvij. </rubric>
                     <incipit>Hoc nobis motus terrarum graues hoc iuges pluuie minabantur</incipit>
                     <explicit>augusto sepulti corporis tenebis hospicio</explicit>
                     <author key="person_100227669">AMBROSE</author>
                     <title key="work_6774">De obitu Theodosii</title>
                     <note><bibl><title>CPL</title> 159</bibl>, <bibl>ed. Otto Faller,
                              <title>CSEL</title> 73 (1955) 369–401.</bibl> The text intrudes before
                        Ambrose’s final epistle (10.77, the next item), of the same title.</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="4" xml:id="St_Johns_College_MS_15-item4">
                     <locus from="174v" to="176r">Fols. 174<hi rend="superscript">vb</hi>–76<hi
                           rend="superscript">ra</hi>:</locus>
                     <rubric>De Inuencione et deposicione sanctorum martirum Geruasij et prothasij
                        lxxviij</rubric>
                     <incipit>Domine sorori uite atque osculis preferende frater Quia nichil
                        sanctitatem tuam</incipit>
                     <explicit>in hodiernum diem differremus reliquias</explicit>
                     <author key="person_100227669">AMBROSE</author>
                     <title key="work_482" type="desc">epistola 77</title>
                     <note><bibl>ed. <title>CSEL</title> 82</bibl>, 3:126–40.</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="5" xml:id="St_Johns_College_MS_15-item5">
                     <locus from="176r" to="182r">Fols. 176<hi rend="superscript">ra</hi>–82<hi
                           rend="superscript">rb</hi></locus>
                     <rubric>Incipit Apologium dauid regis a beato AMBROSIO editum lxxix. </rubric>
                     <incipit>Appologium prophete dauid arripuimus stilo scribere non quo ile
                        indigeat</incipit>
                     <explicit><note type="editorial"><locus from="182r" to="182r">[fol. 182<hi
                                 rend="superscript">ra</hi>]</locus></note> optulere martirio vt
                        cristi sibi graciam mercarentur cui est honor <note type="editorial">[form
                           ending]</note>
                        <gap reason="editorial"/></explicit>
                     <finalRubric>Expliciunt epistole beati AMBROSIJ Mediolan’
                        episcopi</finalRubric>
                     <author key="person_100227669">AMBROSE</author>
                     <title key="work_454">De apologia prophetae Dauid</title>
                     <note><bibl><title>CPL</title> 135</bibl>, <bibl>ed. Karl Schenkl,
                              <title>CSEL</title> 32 (1897) 299–355</bibl>.</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="6" xml:id="St_Johns_College_MS_15-item6">
                     <locus from="183r" to="253r">Fols. 183<hi rend="superscript">ra</hi>–253<hi
                           rend="superscript">rb</hi>:</locus>
                     <incipit>Desiderio desideraui videre faciem uestram et loqui vobiscum multum
                        quidem</incipit>
                     <explicit>iugi supplicacione pulsatus apud dominum intercedat Dat’ Signum
                           iiij<hi rend="superscript">to</hi>. Idus Marcij </explicit>
                     <finalRubric>Expliciunt Epistole sancti THOME CANTUARIENSIS
                        Archiepiscopi</finalRubric>
                     <author key="person_100187947">THOMAS BECKET</author>
                     <title key="work_4786" type="desc">Becket's correspondence</title>
                     <note>most recently <bibl>ed. James Craigie Robertson, <title>Materials for the
                              History of Thomas Becket</title>, RS 67/5–7 (1881–5)</bibl>, with 808
                        letters, as they are here, in a chronological arrangement; see further
                           <bibl>Anne Duggan, <title>Thomas Becket: A Textual History of his
                              Letters</title> (Oxford: Clarendon, 1980).</bibl> The text of our MS
                        is followed <locus from="253r" to="257v">(253<hi rend="superscript"
                              >rb</hi>–7<hi rend="superscript">v</hi>)</locus> by an <title
                           key="work_17092" type="desc">index</title> of the 564 epistles in order,
                        divided into the five sets in which they are presented, with the addressee
                        and incipit for each. (This long-line presentation, in a later hand, begins
                        by being squeezed into the blank remainder of a single column).</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem>
                     <note>Added texts:</note>
                     <msItem n="a">
                        <note>The third and fourth <title key="work_17092" type="desc"
                              >indices</title> to item 1 above: the last twenty lines of <locus
                              from="116r" to="116r">fol. 116<hi rend="superscript">ra</hi></locus>
                           are in an informal <term type="script">anglicana</term>, <date
                              calendar="Gregorian" notBefore="1400" notAfter="1500">s. xv</date>;
                           the remainder in another, using <term type="script">secretary</term>
                           <hi rend="italic">a</hi>, of <date calendar="Gregorian" notBefore="1425"
                              notAfter="1475">s. xv med</date>.</note>
                     </msItem>
                     <msItem n="b">
                        <note>The <title key="work_17092" type="desc">index</title> to item 6 above:
                           in <term type="script">anglicana</term> with <term type="script"
                              >secretary</term>
                           <hi rend="italic">r</hi> and <hi rend="italic">s</hi>, <date
                              calendar="Gregorian" notBefore="1425" notAfter="1475">s. xv
                           med</date>.</note>
                     </msItem>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
